# Always-applied conventions

This repo is a Nix-managed dotfiles setup (nix-darwin + home-manager + flakes) on macOS Apple Silicon. Reference `AGENTS.md` at the repo root for the canonical context — this rule file summarizes the most-load-bearing constraints so Cursor enforces them on every file.

## Stack

- `openspec` 1.3.0 — custom schema `rosh-spec-driven` at `openspec/schemas/rosh-spec-driven/`. Every non-trivial change goes through propose → design → specs → tasks → apply → archive.
- Shell scripts in `hack/` use `set -euo pipefail` and are formatted with `shfmt -i 2 -ci -sr -s`.
- Nix files formatted by `nixfmt-rfc-style` via `nix fmt`.

## Conventions

- Conventional commit titles only, no body. One concern per commit. No formatting-only commits mixed with behavioral changes.
- Never push to `main` unless explicitly directed.
- Never commit unless directed; stage and propose a message instead.
- Never use `--no-verify`, `--no-gpg-sign`, or other hook-bypass flags.
- Never use `any` or type suppressions without explicit permission.
- Never add emojis to code or generated files.
- Never run destructive git commands (`reset --hard`, `clean -f`, `branch -D`, force-push) without explicit instruction.
- Never edit hand-managed configuration when a Nix-managed equivalent exists.
- Never auto-update vendored upstream content; let the sync scripts surface drift.

## Workflow gates

- For impactful actions (`nh darwin switch`, `git push`, `openspec archive`, schema migrations, file deletions outside scratch), verify before, confirm after.
- Use `nix-shell` / `nix develop` for dependencies; avoid global installers.
- Prefer the agent-skills indexed under `~/.claude/skills/` for domain rules.
